                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d33">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/570.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-10-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 14, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Yesterday a communication to the consuls at Hankow from Commander-in-chief Li of
                    the Hupeh army of the Chunghua (Chinese) People’s Government declared that
                    treaties already concluded continue in force; responsibility for the safety of
                    foreign persons and property is assumed; rights hitherto acquired by foreign
                    countries will be protected; indemnities and loans will be paid. But all
                    articles supplied to Imperial Government by foreign nations will be confiscated;
                    treaties hereafter concluded with Imperial Government will not be recognized;
                    foreign powers assisting Imperial Government will be considered enemies. The
                    consuls have made no reply.</p>
                <p>The consular corps have requested the diplomatic corps to ask the Foreign Office
                    that Admiral Sah, due at Hankow tonight, be instructed to avoid as far as
                    possible attacking Wuchang from a position which might draw fire upon the
                    foreign settlements of Hankow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Williams.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
